As the main RSs during PEC process, O2·- and ·OH could be detected by DMPO spin-trapping electron-spin resonance (Fig. 5
                           ). Compared to the TiO2 NRAs and TCN NRAs photoanodes, the enhancement of the O2·- and ·OH signal was observed in the PEC process with the TCNC NRAs photoanode, indicating that doping of CQDs, as an additional electron mediator, could improve the PEC activity for RSs production. RS scavenging experiments were conducted to analyze the PEC mechanism of the TCNC NRAs photoelectrode and quantitatively evaluate the contribution of different RSs on 1,4-D degradation. As shown in Fig. 6
                           , the rate constant of 1,4-D degradation with the TCN NRAs photoelectrode was 0.163 h−1 without quenchers. When IPA (·OH scavenger), NaN3 (·OH and 1O2 scavenger), TMPOL (O2·- scavenger), and Na2C2O4 (h+ scavenger) were added during the PEC process, the rate constants were reduced to 0.132 h−1, 0.105 h−1, 0.049 h−1, and 0.072 h−1, respectively. The maximum inhibition rate of 70.2% observed with the TMPOL addition indicated that O2·- was the main RS during 1,4-D degradation using the TCN NRAs photoelectrode. When the CQDs were doped onto the TCN NRAs electrode (TCNC NRAs electrode), the rate constant of 1,4-D degradation without quenchers increased to 0.250 h−1, which was 1.53 times of that with the TCN NRAs electrode. The faster 1,4-D degradation with the TCNC NRAs electrode could be owing to the increased production of the strong oxidant, such as hydroxyl radical and O2·-. For the TCNC NRAs electrode, IPA and NaN3 dramatically impeded the degradation of 1,4-D, with the rate constants of 0.047 h−1 and 0.023 h−1, respectively. The corresponding inhibition rate reached 81.1% as ·OH was quenched, which was 4 times of that with the TCN NRAs photoelectrode. Therefore, ·OH, as the stronger oxidant (Lee et al., 2004), became the dominated RS, instead of O2·-, for 1,4-D degradation by doping CQDs onto the TCN NRAs photoelectrode. And 1,4-D degradation was accelerated in the PEC process with the TCNC NRAs electrode.
